      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Feb. 1 editorial supports Gov. George Ryan's decision to halt executions in Illinois and appoint a commission to review administration of the death penalty. There is no reason to limit the review to capital cases. Anything that can go wrong in a capital case can go wrong in any criminal case, be it incompetent counsel, faulty identification testimony or failure of the prosecutor to reveal exculpatory evidence.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Feb. 1 editorial supports Gov. George Ryan's decision to halt executions in Illinois and appoint a commission to review administration of the death penalty. There is no reason to limit the review to capital cases. Anything that can go wrong in a capital case can go wrong in any criminal case, be it incompetent counsel, faulty identification testimony or failure of the prosecutor to reveal exculpatory evidence.</p>
        <p>While it is unreasonable to seek a halt in imprisonment pending a study, the entire criminal justice system should be examined nationally. It is time to stop pretending that the system is adequate or that mistakes matter only in death sentences. Twenty years or life imprisonment for an innocent person is no picnic.</p>
        <p>PETER LUSHING  New York, Feb. 1, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor at Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law.</p>
      </block>
